,"1339":"1339","Wymondham, Norfolk, England":"Wymondham, Norfolk, England","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England","Crownthorpe, Norfolk, England":"Crownthorpe, Norfolk, England","England, United Kingdom":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"about 1339–1416":"about 1339–1416","1310–1386":"1310–1386","1353–Male":"1353–Deceased","1359–1415":"1359–1415","1339–1416":"1339–1416","1415":"1415","1359":"1359","1358":"1358","about 1339":"about 1339","1310":"1310","1353":"1353","1386":"1386","1416":"1416","1339":"1339","Wymondham, Norfolk, England":"Wymondham, Norfolk, England","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England","Crownthorpe, Norfolk, England":"Crownthorpe, Norfolk, England","England, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Walcot","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Walcott  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Walcott","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of several places called Walcott, Walcot, or Walcote, for example in Lincolnshire, Leicestershire, Norfolk, Oxfordshire, and Wiltshire, all named in Old English <i>walh</i> ‘foreigner, Briton, serf’ (genitive plural <i>wala</i>) + <i>cot</i> ‘cottage, hut, shelter’ (plural <i>cotu</i>), i.e. ‘the cottage where the (Welsh-speaking) Britons lived’. This name is also frequent in Barbados and Jamaica, when emancipated slaves adopted it from the name of one or other of the sugar plantations owned there by English families called Walcott.","History: This surname was in MA from an early date. William Walcott emigrated from England to Salem, MA, in 1637; John Wolcott (1632–1690) is recorded in Springfield, MA."]}]},{"name":"Margart","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["Formed from Margaret."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Margart Walcot was born about 1339. She married Thomas de Wymondham in 1358, in Crownthorpe, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. She died in 1416, at the age of 78."},"et":{"about 1339–1416":"umbes 1339–1416","1310–1386":"1310–1386","1353–Male":"1353–Surnud","1359–1415":"1359–1415","1339–1416":"1339–1416","1415":"1415","1359":"1359","1358":"1358","about 1339":"umbes 1339","1310":"1310","1353":"1353","1386":"1386","1416":"1416","1339":"1339","Wymondham, Norfolk, England":"Wymondham, Norfolk, England","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England","Crownthorpe, Norfolk, England":"Crownthorpe, Norfolk, England","England, United Kingdom":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1339–1416":"noin 1339–1416","1310–1386":"1310–1386","1353–Male":"1353–Kuollut","1359–1415":"1359–1415","1339–1416":"1339–1416","1415":"1415","1359":"1359","1358":"1358","about 1339":"noin 1339","1310":"1310","1353":"1